        {{/case/leftColumn}}
        {{#> case/rightColumn}}
            <h4>Click test</h4>
            <p>A common hypothesis was that it was difficult to find where to sign up. To look
                into that, I used click tests on <a href="https://www.userzoom.com/">Userzoom</a>. The results? A
                success rate over 90% in all scenarios.</p>

            <h4>User testing</h4>
            <p>I conducted user testing, that I invited the team to watch. The sessions highlighted
                many severe usability issues on mobile, and some smaller problems on desktop.</p>

            <h4>Store experience and international perspective</h4>
            <p>I reviewed
                insights from wider research into the loyalty program in stores around the world.
                The key takeaways were that signing up takes too long, and that the ways to sign up are not adapted to
                all
                markets.</p>

            <h4>Quantitative data</h4>
            <p>To understand the true scale of the issues identified , I looked at <a
                    href="https://analytics.google.com/analytics/">Google Analytics</a> and <a
                    href="https://www.clicktale.com/">Clicktale.</a>
                The figures for mobile (which accounts for 70% of H&M's visitors globally) were not good:
            <ul>
                <li>Signing up took 40 seconds more than on desktop, on average.</li>
                <li>The drop out rate was 30% higher.</li>
            </ul>
            </p>

            <h4>Prioritise and communicate</h4>
            <p>I presented the results to the team. We established our priority for the upcoming sprints, based on
                effort and impact.</p>
            <p>Then, I built a quick showcase for our Sprint Demo. This helped stakeholders to understand our strategy
                and accept that we would not be focusing on some of the new features they were keen on.</p>


